description: The narwhal is a medium-sized toothed whale noted for the long spiral tusk found in males, inhabiting Arctic waters.
They feed on fish, squid and shrimp and are adapted to cold marine environments.
Newts are small amphibians in the salamander family with aquatic larvae and varying terrestrial or aquatic adult phases.
They feed on small invertebrates in ponds and damp habitats.
The numbat is an Australian marsupial that feeds almost exclusively on termites and has distinctive banding on its body.
It is diurnal and forages on the ground using a long sticky tongue.
The nightingale is a small passerine bird known for its powerful and beautiful song, most often heard at dusk and night.
They inhabit woodlands and scrub and feed on invertebrates and berries.
Nutria (coypu) are large semiaquatic rodents introduced in many regions, feeding on aquatic plants and burrowing in banks.
They can impact wetland vegetation and agriculture.
